=========================================
INITIALIZER LISTS (C++11) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is an Initializer List?
------------------------------
- Initializer list is a C++11 feature used to initialize objects using {} braces.
- It provides a uniform way to initialize variables, arrays, and objects.
- Implemented using std::initializer_list.

Example:
int x{10};
int arr[]{1, 2, 3, 4};

-----------------------------------------

2. Why Initializer Lists are needed?
-----------------------------------
Before C++11, initialization had inconsistencies:

int a = 10;
int b(10);
int c{10};  // C++11 unified form

Problems solved:
- Prevents narrowing conversions
- Provides uniform initialization syntax
- Works consistently for all types

-----------------------------------------

3. Narrowing Conversion Prevention (IMPORTANT)
---------------------------------------------
int x = 3.14;   // allowed (loses data)
int y{3.14};    // ❌ ERROR (safe)

Initializer list prevents accidental data loss.

-----------------------------------------

4. std::initializer_list
------------------------
- A lightweight class template in <initializer_list>
- Used to pass list of values to constructors/functions

Example:

#include <initializer_list>
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class MyArray {
public:
    MyArray(initializer_list<int> list) {
        for (auto x : list) {
            cout << x << " ";
        }
    }
};

int main() {
    MyArray obj = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
}

-----------------------------------------

5. Constructor with Initializer List
------------------------------------

class Vector {
    vector<int> v;

public:
    Vector(initializer_list<int> list) {
        for (auto x : list) {
            v.push_back(x);
        }
    }
};

Vector v = {10, 20, 30};

-----------------------------------------

6. Difference: {} vs () Initialization
--------------------------------------

() Initialization:
- May allow narrowing
- Traditional constructor call

{} Initialization:
- Prevents narrowing
- Uniform initialization
- Preferred in modern C++

Example:
int a(5.5);   // allowed (becomes 5)
int b{5.5};   // ❌ error

-----------------------------------------

7. Initializer List in STL
--------------------------
Most STL containers use initializer_list:

vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4};
map<int, int> m = {{1,2}, {3,4}};
set<int> s = {5, 6, 7};

-----------------------------------------

8. auto with Initializer List (IMPORTANT PITFALL)
--------------------------------------------------
auto x = {1, 2, 3};  // type is initializer_list<int>

-----------------------------------------

9. When to use Initializer Lists?
---------------------------------
- Container initialization
- Class constructors with multiple values
- Prevent narrowing conversions
- Clean and readable code

-----------------------------------------

10. Interview Key Points
-----------------------
- Introduced in C++11
- Uses {} uniform initialization
- Prevents narrowing conversions
- Uses std::initializer_list internally
- Widely used in STL containers
- Preferred modern C++ initialization style

